      "content": "Yes, for a darker crust, you should aim for temperatures closer to the higher end of the Maillard reaction range, around 165°C (329°F). However, as this temperature is also close to the point where dough can start to burn, it's important to maintain precise temperature control. The moisture in the dough can slow down the Maillard reaction because it requires dry conditions, but in the case of a hot oven, moisture from steam and the characteristic ferment of the dough will quickly evaporate, allowing the high temperatures around the crust to facilitate the reaction while retaining that crunchy texture. You may need to continuously monitor and adjust temperatures as the bread bakes to achieve the perfect crust.",
